Subject: [PATCH] =?UTF-8?q?fman:=20PCD=20KG=20PR14b-body=20=E2=80=94=20rea?=
 =?UTF-8?q?l=20KGSE=5F*=20programming?=
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Replace the four -EOPNOTSUPP stubs that PR14b-prep landed with the
real implementation. Allocates a free KG scheme id, populates
keygen->schemes[id] with the silicon match-vector built from the
caller's extract spec, and delegates the actual KGSE_* register
write to the existing in-tree keygen_scheme_setup() helper (made
EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL in PR14b-prep).

Supported shape: IPv4 5-tuple (SIP/DIP/proto/SPORT/DPORT). Wider
shapes return -EOPNOTSUPP loudly rather than silently degrading.

attach_cc() remains -EOPNOTSUPP — CCBS wiring requires PR14c's
struct fman_pcd_cc_tree.

Reference: LS1046A RM §8.7.4–8.7.5 (KGSE_MV/MODE/EKDV/EKFC/CCBS/
HC/FQB) plus in-tree fman_keygen.c silicon-bit definitions.

Build: native ARM64 on Cobalt 100, zero warnings, all four symbols
present in System.map with __ksymtab entries.
---
 .../net/ethernet/freescale/fman/fman_pcd_kg.c | 389 +++++++++++++++---
 1 file changed, 341 insertions(+), 48 deletions(-)

diff --git a/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/fman/fman_pcd_kg.c b/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/fman/fman_pcd_kg.c
index f14ddf9f3..366537be7 100644
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/fman/fman_pcd_kg.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/fman/fman_pcd_kg.c
@@ -1,92 +1,354 @@
 // SPDX-License-Identifier: GPL-2.0
 /*
- * FMan PCD KeyGen (KG) - PR14b-prep stub.
+ * FMan PCD KeyGen (KG) - silicon-programming layer.
  *
- * Authoritative reference: LS1046A Reference Manual sec 8.7.4 (scheme
- * registers KGSE_MV/MODE/EKDV/EKFC/CCBS/HC/FQB) and 8.7.5 (extract
- * record format).  The actual silicon-programming body lands in
- * PR14b-body and is authored RM-authoritative, with SDK + we-are-mono as silicon-behaviour cross-refs (spec v1.1) plus the existing
- * in-tree register definitions in fman_keygen.c.
+ * PR14b-body of the ASK2 v1.0 PR14 series.  Replaces the four
+ * -EOPNOTSUPP stubs that PR14b-prep landed with a real
+ * implementation that allocates a free KG scheme, populates
+ * keygen->schemes[scheme_id] from the caller-supplied
+ * struct fman_pcd_kg_scheme_params, and delegates the actual
+ * KGSE_* register programming to the existing in-tree helper
+ * keygen_scheme_setup() (made EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL by PR14b-prep).
  *
- * What PR14b-prep delivers
- * ------------------------
- * Only the public API surface required so that ask.ko can link against
- * fsl_dpaa_fman.ko today and skip its FMan-offload code path cleanly
- * when KG is not yet wired up.  Every entry point returns -EOPNOTSUPP
- * (or ERR_PTR(-EOPNOTSUPP) for the constructor) so a consumer can
- * detect the stub at runtime without crashing.  The opaque
- * struct fman_pcd_kg_scheme is fully defined here so sizeof() works
- * inside this TU when PR14b-body extends it; consumers see only the
- * forward declaration in <linux/fsl/fman_pcd.h>.
+ * Authoritative reference
+ * -----------------------
+ * - LS1046A Reference Manual sec 8.7.4 (KGSE_MV/MODE/EKDV/EKFC/CCBS/
+ *   HC/FQB scheme registers).
+ * - LS1046A Reference Manual sec 8.7.5 (KGSE extract record format,
+ *   EKDV slot layout, hash configuration).
+ * - LS1046A Reference Manual sec 8.4 (FMan port numbering: 1-8 1G,
+ *   9-10 10G; port 0 is the offline-parsing port and is never a
+ *   valid KG match-vector target).
+ * - drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/fman/fman_keygen.c in this same
+ *   build tree provides the silicon-fact register names + bit
+ *   layouts (KG_SCH_*, KG_SCH_KN_*, KG_SCH_HASH_CONFIG_SHIFT_SHIFT)
+ *   and the existing helpers we delegate to.
  *
- * Symbol visibility: all four public entry points are EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL
- * because ask.ko (out-of-tree, GPL) is the sole consumer; the rest of
- * the kernel must not call into the KG layer directly.
+ * Locking model
+ * -------------
+ * pcd->lock (acquired via fman_pcd_get_lock()) serialises scheme-id
+ * allocation, list mutation, and the keygen_scheme_setup() write
+ * path.  ask.ko's M5 fast path does NOT enter this layer per packet
+ * - the hardware does the lookup directly against the MURAM-resident
+ * table programmed by the slow-path callers.
  *
- * Locking: at PR14b-prep there is no state to lock.  PR14b-body will
- * take pcd->lock (via fman_pcd_get_lock()) around the
- * keygen_scheme_setup() / keygen_bind_port_to_schemes() calls promoted
- * to module-internal scope in this same patch.
+ * What is intentionally still a stub
+ * ----------------------------------
+ * fman_pcd_kg_attach_cc() remains -EOPNOTSUPP at PR14b-body.  The
+ * CCBS (CC Base Scheme) wiring depends on PR14c's struct
+ * fman_pcd_cc_tree and that .c file does not exist yet.  When PR14c
+ * lands we will revisit attach_cc and add the kgse_ccbs/cc_index
+ * programming via a small follow-up patch.
  */
 
 #include <linux/err.h>
+#include <linux/errno.h>
 #include <linux/export.h>
 #include <linux/kernel.h>
 #include <linux/list.h>
 #include <linux/module.h>
+#include <linux/mutex.h>
 #include <linux/slab.h>
 #include <linux/types.h>
 
 #include <linux/fsl/fman_pcd.h>
+#include "fman.h"
+#include "fman_keygen_internal.h"
 #include "fman_pcd_internal.h"
 
 /*
- * Opaque KG scheme handle.  Only the fields touched by PR14b-prep are
- * declared; PR14b-body will extend this with the cached register values
- * (mv/mode/ekdv[8]/ccbs/fqb), the per-scheme spinlock, and the parent
- * pcd back-pointer needed for fman_pcd_kg_scheme_destroy() to unlink
- * from pcd->kg_schemes under pcd->lock.
+ * KeyGen scheme match-vector silicon bits (RM §8.7.4, KGSE_MV register).
+ * These are private to fman_keygen.c upstream; replicated here as silicon
+ * constants for the public PCD KG API. Do NOT change values — they are
+ * hardware-fixed.
+ */
+#define KG_SCH_KN_PTYPE1	0x00040000
+#define KG_SCH_KN_IPSRC1	0x00100000
+#define KG_SCH_KN_IPDST1	0x00080000
+#define KG_SCH_KN_L4PSRC	0x00000004
+#define KG_SCH_KN_L4PDST	0x00000002
+
+/*
+ * KG extract-source enumeration that mirrors the silicon-side
+ * KGSE_EKDV slot encoding documented in RM sec 8.7.5 Table 8-105.
+ * The KG_SCH_DEF_USE_KGSE_DV_{0,1} constants in fman_keygen.c hold
+ * the silicon values 2 and 3 (parse-result for the IPv4 5-tuple
+ * standard slots).  Our public enum is layered on top: ask.ko
+ * supplies values from enum fman_pcd_kg_extract_from in
+ * <linux/fsl/fman_pcd.h>; we translate them here.
+ */
+static int kg_extract_src_valid(enum fman_pcd_kg_extract_from src)
+{
+switch (src) {
+case FMAN_PCD_KG_EXTRACT_FROM_FRAME:
+case FMAN_PCD_KG_EXTRACT_FROM_PARSE_RESULT:
+case FMAN_PCD_KG_EXTRACT_FROM_DEFAULT:
+return 0;
+}
+return -EINVAL;
+}
+
+/*
+ * Per-scheme bookkeeping kept on the pcd->kg_schemes list.  The body
+ * we extend here adds the parent pcd back-pointer (needed by
+ * scheme_destroy to splice ourselves out), the silicon-allocated
+ * scheme id, and a small cache of the extract spec the caller
+ * supplied (so debugfs can show the programmed shape without
+ * re-decoding KGSE_EKDV).  The handle remains opaque to consumers -
+ * <linux/fsl/fman_pcd.h> only forward-declares this struct.
  */
 struct fman_pcd_kg_scheme {
-struct list_head node;        /* link into pcd->kg_schemes */
-struct fman_pcd *pcd;         /* parent subsystem, never NULL */
-u8 id;                        /* 0..31 on FMan v3 LS1046A */
+struct list_head node;
+struct fman_pcd *pcd;
+u8 id;
+u8 hw_port_id;        /* 0 = unbound; set by bind_port */
+bool bound;
+u8 num_extracts;
+struct fman_pcd_kg_extract_spec extracts[8];
+u32 default_fqid;
+bool use_hash;
 };
 
+/*
+ * Allocate the next free scheme id.  Caller must hold pcd->lock.
+ *
+ * Semantics:
+ *   - @params->id >= 0: caller wants a specific slot; succeed only
+ *     if it is currently free.
+ *   - @params->id < 0:  first-fit allocation in [0, FM_KG_MAX_NUM_OF_SCHEMES).
+ *
+ * Returns the allocated id in [0, FM_KG_MAX_NUM_OF_SCHEMES) on
+ * success or a negative errno on failure.  Does NOT mark the slot
+ * used - keygen_scheme_setup() sets keygen->schemes[id].used itself.
+ */
+static int kg_alloc_scheme_id(struct fman_keygen *keygen,
+      const struct fman_pcd_kg_scheme_params *params)
+{
+int i;
+
+if (params->id >= 0) {
+if (params->id >= FM_KG_MAX_NUM_OF_SCHEMES)
+return -EINVAL;
+if (keygen->schemes[params->id].used)
+return -EBUSY;
+return params->id;
+}
+
+for (i = 0; i < FM_KG_MAX_NUM_OF_SCHEMES; i++)
+if (!keygen->schemes[i].used)
+return i;
+
+return -ENOSPC;
+}
+
+/*
+ * Translate the caller's extract spec to a silicon match-vector.
+ * RM sec 8.7.5 documents the KGSE_KN (Key Number) bits; the
+ * KG_SCH_KN_* constants in fman_keygen.c hold the silicon bit
+ * positions.  At PR14b-body we support the IPv4 5-tuple shape
+ * (SIP, DIP, proto, SPORT, DPORT) because that is exactly what
+ * ask.ko M5's first flow installer needs.  Wider shapes (IPv6,
+ * MPLS, IPSEC) extend this function in PR14b follow-ups - they all
+ * map to bits that already exist in fman_keygen.c.
+ *
+ * Returns 0 + writes to *out on success, or a negative errno.
+ */
+static int kg_build_match_vector(const struct fman_pcd_kg_scheme_params *p,
+ u32 *out)
+{
+u32 mv = 0;
+u8 i;
+
+for (i = 0; i < p->num_extracts; i++) {
+const struct fman_pcd_kg_extract_spec *e = &p->extracts[i];
+
+if (kg_extract_src_valid(e->src))
+return -EINVAL;
+if (e->size == 0 || e->size > 16)
+return -EINVAL;
+if (e->src == FMAN_PCD_KG_EXTRACT_FROM_PARSE_RESULT &&
+    e->offset > 63)
+return -EINVAL;
+if (e->src == FMAN_PCD_KG_EXTRACT_FROM_FRAME &&
+    e->offset > 127)
+return -EINVAL;
+
+/*
+ * Synthetic mapping: at PR14b-body we only honour the
+ * five canonical IPv4 5-tuple slots and let everything
+ * else fall through to the generic-extract bank (no
+ * special bit set, KeyGen uses default extract).  This
+ * is sufficient for ask.ko's IPv4-only M5 first cut;
+ * the full opcode table can be wired up in a follow-up
+ * once we have a real test harness.
+ */
+switch (e->offset) {
+case 12:  /* parse_result.IPv4 SIP */
+mv |= KG_SCH_KN_IPSRC1;
+break;
+case 16:  /* parse_result.IPv4 DIP */
+mv |= KG_SCH_KN_IPDST1;
+break;
+case 9:   /* parse_result.IPv4 protocol */
+mv |= KG_SCH_KN_PTYPE1;
+break;
+case 20:  /* parse_result.L4 SPORT */
+mv |= KG_SCH_KN_L4PSRC;
+break;
+case 22:  /* parse_result.L4 DPORT */
+mv |= KG_SCH_KN_L4PDST;
+break;
+default:
+/* Unrecognised offset is non-fatal: the caller
+ * still gets a working scheme with the canonical
+ * slots that DID match.  PR14b-body returns
+ * -EINVAL to surface the unsupported shape
+ * loudly rather than silently producing an
+ * unexpected lookup.
+ */
+return -EOPNOTSUPP;
+}
+}
+
+if (mv == 0)
+return -EINVAL;
+
+*out = mv;
+return 0;
+}
+
 struct fman_pcd_kg_scheme *
 fman_pcd_kg_scheme_create(struct fman_pcd *pcd,
   const struct fman_pcd_kg_scheme_params *params)
 {
+struct fman_pcd_kg_scheme *scheme;
+struct fman_keygen *keygen;
+struct keygen_scheme *slot;
+struct fman *fman;
+struct mutex *lock;
+u32 match_vector;
+int id, err;
+
 if (!pcd || !params)
 return ERR_PTR(-EINVAL);
-
 if (params->num_extracts == 0 || params->num_extracts > 8)
 return ERR_PTR(-EINVAL);
+if (params->default_fqid == 0 ||
+    params->default_fqid >= (1U << 24))
+return ERR_PTR(-EINVAL);
+
+fman = fman_pcd_get_fman(pcd);
+if (!fman || !fman->keygen)
+return ERR_PTR(-ENXIO);
+keygen = fman->keygen;
+lock = fman_pcd_get_lock(pcd);
+
+err = kg_build_match_vector(params, &match_vector);
+if (err)
+return ERR_PTR(err);
+
+scheme = kzalloc(sizeof(*scheme), GFP_KERNEL);
+if (!scheme)
+return ERR_PTR(-ENOMEM);
+
+mutex_lock(lock);
+id = kg_alloc_scheme_id(keygen, params);
+if (id < 0) {
+err = id;
+goto err_unlock;
+}
 
 /*
- * PR14b-body lands the real allocator + KGSE_* register
- * programming.  Today we refuse cleanly so ask.ko's M5 KG
- * path falls back to its software-FIB until the silicon
- * code is in place.
+ * Populate the silicon-side scheme slot.  The existing
+ * keygen_scheme_setup() helper reads from here.  hw_port_id
+ * stays 0 until bind_port wires us up; setup() does not
+ * dispatch frames into a scheme until match_vector AND the
+ * port-binding ar register both reference it.
+ */
+slot = &keygen->schemes[id];
+memset(slot, 0, sizeof(*slot));
+slot->match_vector = match_vector;
+slot->base_fqid = params->default_fqid;
+slot->use_hashing = params->use_hash;
+if (params->use_hash) {
+/* Conservative defaults for the M5 first cut.  The
+ * field-level tuning (hash_fqid_count, symmetric_hash,
+ * hashShift) becomes a public API parameter in
+ * PR14b-body-tuning if/when ask.ko needs more than
+ * one FQID per scheme.
  */
-return ERR_PTR(-EOPNOTSUPP);
+slot->hash_fqid_count = 1;
+slot->symmetric_hash = true;
+slot->hashShift = 0;
+}
+
+err = keygen_scheme_setup(keygen, (u8)id, true);
+if (err) {
+memset(slot, 0, sizeof(*slot));
+goto err_unlock;
+}
+
+scheme->pcd          = pcd;
+scheme->id           = (u8)id;
+scheme->hw_port_id   = 0;
+scheme->bound        = false;
+scheme->num_extracts = params->num_extracts;
+memcpy(scheme->extracts, params->extracts,
+       params->num_extracts * sizeof(scheme->extracts[0]));
+scheme->default_fqid = params->default_fqid;
+scheme->use_hash     = params->use_hash;
+INIT_LIST_HEAD(&scheme->node);
+list_add_tail(&scheme->node, fman_pcd_get_kg_list(pcd));
+
+mutex_unlock(lock);
+return scheme;
+
+err_unlock:
+mutex_unlock(lock);
+kfree(scheme);
+return ERR_PTR(err);
 }
 EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL(fman_pcd_kg_scheme_create);
 
 int fman_pcd_kg_bind_port(struct fman_pcd_kg_scheme *scheme, u8 port_id)
 {
+struct fman_keygen *keygen;
+struct keygen_scheme *slot;
+struct fman *fman;
+struct mutex *lock;
+int err;
+
 if (!scheme)
 return -EINVAL;
-
-/*
- * LS1046A FMan v3 has 8x 1G MACs (ports 1-8) plus 2x 10G
- * MACs (ports 9-10) per RM 8.4.  Port id 0 is reserved for
- * the offline parsing port and is never a valid KG target.
- */
 if (port_id == 0 || port_id > 10)
 return -EINVAL;
 
-return -EOPNOTSUPP;
+fman = fman_pcd_get_fman(scheme->pcd);
+if (!fman || !fman->keygen)
+return -ENXIO;
+keygen = fman->keygen;
+lock = fman_pcd_get_lock(scheme->pcd);
+
+mutex_lock(lock);
+if (scheme->bound) {
+mutex_unlock(lock);
+return -EBUSY;
+}
+
+slot = &keygen->schemes[scheme->id];
+slot->hw_port_id = port_id;
+
+err = keygen_bind_port_to_schemes(keygen, scheme->id, true);
+if (err) {
+slot->hw_port_id = 0;
+mutex_unlock(lock);
+return err;
+}
+
+scheme->hw_port_id = port_id;
+scheme->bound      = true;
+mutex_unlock(lock);
+return 0;
 }
 EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL(fman_pcd_kg_bind_port);
 
@@ -96,20 +358,51 @@ int fman_pcd_kg_attach_cc(struct fman_pcd_kg_scheme *scheme,
 if (!scheme || !cc)
 return -EINVAL;
 
+/*
+ * Deferred to PR14b follow-up: requires struct fman_pcd_cc_tree
+ * which lands in PR14c (fman_pcd_cc.c).  Programming target is
+ * KGSE_CCBS (RM sec 8.7.4): hash output indexes into the CC tree's
+ * key table.  When PR14c lands we will:
+ *   1. mutex_lock(pcd->lock)
+ *   2. validate scheme->bound (cannot chain an unbound scheme)
+ *   3. clear KG_SCH_MODE_EN, rewrite KGSE_CCBS, set CC chain bit,
+ *      set KG_SCH_MODE_EN
+ *   4. mutex_unlock
+ */
 return -EOPNOTSUPP;
 }
 EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL(fman_pcd_kg_attach_cc);
 
 void fman_pcd_kg_scheme_destroy(struct fman_pcd_kg_scheme *scheme)
 {
+struct fman_keygen *keygen;
+struct fman *fman;
+struct mutex *lock;
+
 if (!scheme)
 return;
 
+fman = fman_pcd_get_fman(scheme->pcd);
+if (!fman || !fman->keygen) {
 /*
- * No real allocation happens at PR14b-prep, so there is
- * nothing to free.  PR14b-body will take pcd->lock, splice
- * scheme->node out of pcd->kg_schemes, clear the KGSE_*
- * registers for scheme->id, and kfree(scheme).
+ * Probe-failure tear-down can land here if the FMan
+ * keygen has already been freed.  Drop the wrapper
+ * without touching silicon - the parent FMan unbind
+ * path will reset KGSE_* anyway.
  */
+kfree(scheme);
+return;
+}
+keygen = fman->keygen;
+lock = fman_pcd_get_lock(scheme->pcd);
+
+mutex_lock(lock);
+if (scheme->bound)
+(void)keygen_bind_port_to_schemes(keygen, scheme->id, false);
+(void)keygen_scheme_setup(keygen, scheme->id, false);
+list_del(&scheme->node);
+mutex_unlock(lock);
+
+kfree(scheme);
 }
 EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL(fman_pcd_kg_scheme_destroy);
